4️⃣ Cache Flow
1️⃣ Read Flow (Cache-Aside / Lazy Loading)

Most common caching pattern

Step-by-step
Client → Service → Cache (Redis)
                 ↓ (miss)
               Database
                 ↓
              Save in Cache
                 ↓
               Return Response

Explanation

Client requests data (ex: account balance)

Service checks Redis cache

If cache hit → return immediately ⚡

If cache miss → read from DB

Store DB result in Redis

Return to client

Example (Banking)
GET /account/1001/balance


Flow

Check → account:balance:1001 in Redis

If present → return instantly

If not → fetch from MySQL → store in Redis → return

2️⃣ Write Flow (Cache Update Strategy)

When data changes (deposit/withdraw), cache must stay consistent.

Option A — Write Through (Safe)
Update DB → Update Cache → Return


✔ Always consistent
❌ Slightly slower

Option B — Cache Evict (Most Used)
Update DB → Delete Cache → Next read reloads cache


✔ Simple + reliable
✔ Used in most real systems

Option C — Write Back (Advanced)
Update Cache → Async DB update


✔ Fast
❌ Risky (data loss if crash)

Used in high-frequency trading / analytics only.

3️⃣ Spring Boot Cache Flow (Real Implementation)
Read (Cacheable)
@Cacheable(value = "accountBalance", key = "#accountId")
public Double getBalance(Long accountId) {
    return accountRepository.findBalance(accountId);
}


What happens internally

First call → DB hit → stored in Redis

Next calls → returned from Redis (no DB hit)

Write (Evict Cache)
@CacheEvict(value = "accountBalance", key = "#accountId")
public void deposit(Long accountId, Double amount) {
    accountRepository.deposit(accountId, amount);
}


Why evict?

Because balance changed → old cache invalid ❌

4️⃣ Full Cache Lifecycle
READ
 ├─ Cache Hit → Fast response ⚡
 └─ Cache Miss → DB → Save in Cache → Return

WRITE
 ├─ Update DB
 ├─ Evict / Update Cache
 └─ Next Read → Fresh Cache

5️⃣ Real Banking Example Flow
First Request
GET balance
Redis → MISS
DB → 25,000
Redis ← Save
Return → 25,000

Second Request
GET balance
Redis → HIT
Return → 25,000 ⚡

After Deposit ₹5,000
Update DB → 30,000
Evict Cache
Next Read → DB → Save → Return → 30,000

🧠 Interview Answer (Short)

“Cache-Aside pattern is used where application first checks Redis. On miss, data is fetched from DB and stored in cache. On update, cache is evicted or updated to maintain consistency.”
Client → Service
        ↓
   Check Redis
   ↓        ↓
Cache Hit   Cache Miss
   ↓           ↓
Return      Query DB → Save to Redis → Return

